               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I bought the goods of 
               <persName id="t17751206-70-person1026">
                  Esther
                   Moses
               <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1026" type="surname" value="Moses"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1026" type="given" value="Esther"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1026" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and her daughter; they were tried on Saturday for stealing them, and I for receiving them; and we were all acquitted: I was never charged with having stole the goods.</p>
               <p>FOR THE PRISONER.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17751206-70-person1027">
                  BENJAMIN
                   LYON
               <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1027" type="surname" value="LYON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1027" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-70-person1027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>am a hatter in Shoemaker-row, Aldgate:<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177512060092"></xptr> I have known the prisoner fourteen or fifteen years. On the 5th of November I saw the prisoner at a benefit club in Prescot-street: he came in just after four, and staid till after nine or ten o'clock: it was a quarterly night; there are five men besides the stewards appointed to see the books right, the prisoner was one of them.</p>
